### Structure of the Article

Main page: [Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Layout](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout)

A well-constructed article, much like a well-constructed argument, begins with a compelling introduction, proceeds through a clear and logical structure, and concludes with standard appendices. Anything less is merely a collection of words, adrift in the digital ether.

#### Introductory Material / Lead

Further information: § Lead section, and [Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lead_section](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lead_section)

Every article, without exception, commences with a [lead section](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lead_section) ([WP:CREATELEAD](/Wikipedia:CREATELEAD)). This is not merely a suggestion; it is a fundamental design choice, intended to provide an immediate, digestible summary of the topic's most salient points. This crucial section precedes the very first header, setting the stage. It may contain a [lead image](/MOS:LEADIMAGE), a visual shorthand representative of the topic, and/or an [infobox](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Infoboxes) offering a few key, often statistical, facts – dates, measurements, and other such dry but essential data.

The lead, in its ideal form, functions as a standalone overview, a concise encapsulation of the article's subject. Its purpose is threefold: to identify the topic, establish its context within the broader tapestry of knowledge, and, most critically, to explain precisely why the topic is [notable](/Wikipedia:Notability). The opening sentences are not merely decorative; they are a concentrated dose of the most noteworthy features, the essential facts that any reader, even a fleeting one, *must* apprehend. Crucially, any significant information presented in the lead *must* be elaborated upon in the main body of the article; the lead is a promise of further detail, not a repository for isolated facts. Each major section that follows should find its appropriate, condensed representation within the lead, including any prominent controversies, handled with the utmost care to avoid violating the [WP:Neutral point of view](/Wikipedia:Neutral_point_of_view) by granting undue attention to lesser disputes, trivial details, or effusive praise. The emphasis, both in the lead and the body, should [reflect its importance to the topic](/Wikipedia:DUE), as determined by [reliable, published sources](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). This isn't about personal preference; it's about objective weight.

These lead sections typically reside within a comfortable range of no more than approximately 400 words. Citations, while generally optional here, are sometimes necessary; consult [WP:CITELEAD](/Wikipedia:CITELEAD) for the finer points.

#### Paragraphs

*   [Shortcut](/Wikipedia:Shortcut)
*   • WP:PARAGRAPH[WP:PARAGRAPH](/Wikipedia:PARAGRAPH)
*   See also: [Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout § Paragraphs](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout)

Paragraphs, the fundamental building blocks of prose, should possess a paradoxical quality: short enough to be digestible, yet sufficiently expansive to fully develop a single idea. Each paragraph should be a self-contained unit, dedicated to a particular point or concept, with every sentence within it orbiting that central theme. When the subject shifts, a new paragraph must commence. The common editorial failing of overly long, sprawling paragraphs should be remedied by judicious splitting.

A frequent transgression involves paragraphs that are, in essence, [tables](/Help:Table) or [lists](/Help:List) masquerading as prose. Such abominations should be ruthlessly rewritten into proper prose or, failing that, converted to their unmasked, structured form. [Wikipedia:When to use tables](/Wikipedia:When_to_use_tables) and [Wikipedia:Embedded list](/Wikipedia:Embedded_list) offer illuminating guidance on the appropriate deployment of these elements.

#### Headings

Headings serve as signposts, clarifying the article's structure and populating the table of contents. To understand the MediaWiki software's interaction with these structural elements, refer to [Help:Section](/Help:Section).

Headings operate within a strict hierarchy. The article's title itself implicitly occupies a level 1 heading, thus your structural journey begins with a level 2 heading ( `==Heading==` ), followed by progressively lower levels: `===Subheading===`, `====Subsubheading====`, and so forth. The decision of whether extensive subtopics warrant their own page or remain within a larger one is a matter of editorial judgment, often a source of endless debate. Consult § Summary style below for further illumination on this delicate balance.

A cardinal rule: headings should *not* contain [links](/Help:Link). The very purpose of a heading is to introduce a segment of information, to inform the reader of the subtopic at hand. Links to other articles belong within the flowing text of the section itself, where they can be properly contextualized.

#### Images

Should the article lend itself to visual enhancement – a rare moment of aesthetic consideration – these images must be judiciously placed. They should reside in proximity to the text they illustrate, forming a coherent visual and textual narrative. For further insights into the art of image placement, consult [Wikipedia:Layout § Images](/Wikipedia:Layout) and [Wikipedia:Picture tutorial](/Wikipedia:Picture_tutorial).

#### Standard Appendices

As meticulously detailed at [Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout § Standard appendices and footers](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout), a series of optional appendix sections may grace the conclusion of an article, following the main body, in a prescribed order. This is not arbitrary; it is a concession to logical organization.

*   A definitive list of books or other works authored or created by the subject of the article ([works](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout)).
*   A curated collection of internal "[wikilinks](/Wikipedia:Wikilinks)" directing the reader to related Wikipedia articles ([see also](/Wikipedia:Layout)).
*   The indispensable notes and references, the very bedrock of verifiability ([notes, footnotes, or references](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout)).
*   A list of recommended relevant books, articles, or other publications that, while pertinent, were not explicitly utilized as sources ([further reading](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout)).
*   A compilation of recommended relevant websites that similarly were not employed as direct sources ([external links](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout)).

With a few exceptions, any [links to sister projects](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout) – the extended family of Wikimedia – are relegated to these "further reading" or "external links" sections. Finally, [succession boxes and navigational footers](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Layout) find their place at the absolute end of the article, following the last appendix, but preceding the category and interwiki templates. A precise order, for a precise world.

### Size

*   [Shortcut](/Wikipedia:Shortcut)
*   • WP:BETTER#SIZE[WP:BETTER#SIZE](/Wikipedia:BETTER)
*   See also: [Wikipedia:Article_size](/Wikipedia:Article_size) and [Wikipedia:Infobox_too_large](/Wikipedia:Infobox_too_large)

Well-developed articles, those that truly serve their purpose, typically occupy a textual landscape of between 2,000 and 5,000 words. However, the universe, and thus its documentation, is not always so neatly contained; some topics simply demand more expansive treatment. Articles that swell to excessive proportions, becoming unwieldy and cumbersome, are candidates for [splitting](/Wikipedia:SPLIT) into more manageable, smaller articles. This improves both readability for the weary reader and ease of editing for the diligent contributor. Alternatively, such behemoths may necessitate rigorous trimming to restore them to a state of [conciseness](/Wikipedia:CONCISE). When a section is excised and moved, the original article should retain a concise version under an italicized header, such as `Main article: [History of Ruritania](/Ruritania)`. (A comprehensive list of templates for creating these headers is thoughtfully provided at [Category:Wikipedia page-section templates](/Category:Wikipedia_page-section_templates)). Without this contextual breadcrumb, the overall coherence suffers, and the reader is left adrift. It is imperative that each article on a subtopic be crafted as a truly stand-alone piece, capable of being understood and appreciated without requiring prior immersion in the main article.

When a subject is vast – consider the sprawling narrative of [World War II](/World_War_II) – and spawns numerous sub-articles, the primary article demands a delicate balance. Avoid the common pitfall of granting undue weight to one particular segment at the expense of others. In shorter articles, a disproportionate amount of text dedicated to a single subtopic often signals that this subtopic has outgrown its current home and should be granted its own page, leaving only a succinct summary on the main page. This is not an act of dismissal, but an act of strategic organization.

### Articles Covering Subtopics

The very nature of Wikipedia, a constantly evolving repository of knowledge, often dictates a natural progression toward the creation of new articles. Any given article's text, upon closer inspection, frequently comprises a sequence of related but distinct subtopics. When a particular subtopic accumulates enough textual mass to warrant its own dedicated article, that text can be elegantly [summarized](/Wikipedia:Summary_style) within the parent article, accompanied by a clear link to the more detailed, newly spun-off piece. The article on [Cricket](/Cricket) stands as a prime illustration of this principle: it is meticulously divided into subsections, each offering an overview of the sport's various facets, with each subsection gracefully directing the reader to one or more comprehensive subtopic articles. It's a pragmatic approach to managing an ever-expanding universe of information.

### Information Style and Tone

*   [Shortcuts](/Wikipedia:Shortcut)
*   • WP:ENCSTYLE[WP:ENCSTYLE](/Wikipedia:ENCSTYLE)
*   • WP:INFSTYLE[WP:INFSTYLE](/WP:INFSTYLE)

Two primary styles, intrinsically linked and by no means mutually exclusive, tend to dominate the landscape of Wikipedia articles. The [tone](/Tone_(literature)), however, is a constant: it must remain formal, impersonal, and dispassionate. Anything less is an affront to the encyclopedic mission.

These prevailing styles are:

*   **Summary style**, which dictates the logical arrangement of a broad topic into a main article and its associated side articles, each further subdivided into coherent subtopical sections.
*   **Inverted pyramid style** (also known as news style), which prioritizes information by placing the most critical details at the apex, followed by supporting material and finer points, with background information receding towards the base.

A defining characteristic shared by both styles, and indeed by all Wikipedia articles, is the indispensable [lead section](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lead_section) – a concise, summarizing overview of the topic's most vital facts. The [infobox](/Wikipedia:Infobox) template, frequently encountered at the top of many articles, represents an even further distillation of these key points, a visual abstract for the truly impatient.

#### Summary Style

Main page: [Wikipedia:Summary_style](/Wikipedia:Summary_style)

Summary style, a pragmatic approach to knowledge organization, can be applied both across entire categories of articles and within the confines of a single article. Material is thoughtfully grouped and segmented into sections that inherently form discrete subtopics. Over time, as the main article inevitably expands, these subtopics may [spin off](/Wikipedia:SPINOFF) into separate articles to prevent the main entry from exceeding a reasonable [article length](/Wikipedia:Article_length). When such a subtopic achieves its independence, a concise summary is left in its wake, accompanied by a pointer (typically utilizing the `{{[Main](/Template:Main)}}` template) directing the reader to the newly created, more detailed side article.

The advantages of employing summary style are manifold, and rather self-evident:

*   **Tailored Detail:** Readers, being diverse creatures, possess varying appetites for detail. This style graciously permits them to choose their desired level of immersion. Some desire only a fleeting overview, satisfied by the lead section; others seek a moderate amount of information, finding the main article perfectly suited to their needs; and yet others crave an exhaustive exploration, eagerly delving into the specialized side articles. It's a choose-your-own-adventure of information.
*   **Readability Management:** An article that swells to an unwieldy length becomes a chore, an obstacle rather than a conduit to knowledge. The systematic process of summarizing and spinning off material prevents the reader from being overwhelmed by an impenetrable wall of text.
*   **Content Refinement:** Excessively detailed articles often suffer from redundancy or verbose writing. The disciplined application of summary style naturally encourages the elimination of repetition and bloat, forcing a more concise expression. This, of course, comes with the minor trade-off of some necessary cross-article redundancy (i.e., the summary of one article appearing in another), a small price to pay for clarity.

The precise organizational principle governing a particular summary-style article is inherently dependent on context. Various options present themselves, such as chronological progression, geographical demarcation, or the rigid order of alphabetization (primarily in lists), among other logical frameworks.

Illustrative examples of this style include the former featured articles [Association football](/Association_football) and [Music of the Lesser Antilles](/Music_of_the_Lesser_Antilles). They stand as testaments to the power of structured information.

#### Inverted Pyramid

*   [Shortcut](/Wikipedia:Shortcut)
*   • WP:PYRAMID[WP:PYRAMID](/Wikipedia:PYRAMID)
*   See also: [Wikipedia:Too_long;_didn%27t_read](/Wikipedia:Too_long;_didn%27t_read)

Some articles, particularly those dealing with transient events, consciously adopt the [inverted pyramid](/Inverted_pyramid_(journalism)) structure, a venerable tradition borrowed from [journalism](/Journalism). This approach, familiar from news articles, gets straight to the point, delivering the most critical information upfront. Its defining characteristic is the placement of essential details at the very beginning, with the importance of information progressively diminishing as the article unfolds. This style was originally devised to allow editors to trim articles from the bottom to fit available layout space – a rather practical, if somewhat brutal, origin. It fosters brevity and prioritizes information, catering to the reader's natural expectation of encountering the most vital material early on, before interest inevitably wanes.

It must be stated, for the record, that encyclopedia articles are *not* universally required to adhere to the inverted pyramid order. Often, a chronological, geographical, or other logical structure proves to be a superior fit for the subject matter. However, a familiarity with this convention can be invaluable when planning the style and layout of an article where such an approach is particularly apt. Common applications include descriptions of short-term events, concise biographies of individuals notable for a singular achievement, and other articles where the proliferation of logical subtopics is unlikely, but a clear prioritization of facts for the reader is paramount.

The [lead section](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Lead_section) of any article, and indeed many nascent [stub](/Wikipedia:Stub) articles, inherently employ elements of the inverted pyramid approach. Consequently, a great many articles commence their existence as inverted-pyramid pieces, gradually incorporating features of summary style as they mature and expand. Furthermore, individual sections within a larger article can also benefit from this structure, ensuring that readers merely skimming the content still absorb the most important information before moving on.

#### Tone

*   [Shortcuts](/Wikipedia:Shortcut)
*   • WP:TONE[WP:TONE](/Wikipedia:TONE)
*   • WP:SLANG[WP:SLANG](/Wikipedia:SLANG)
*   "WP:SLANG" redirects here. For the policy that covers writing Wikipedia articles about slang terms, see [WP:NOTSLANG](/Wikipedia:Wikipedia_is_not_a_dictionary).
*   See also: [Wikipedia:Neutral_point_of_view § Impartial tone](/Wikipedia:Neutral_point_of_view), and [Wikipedia:Biographies_of_living_persons § Tone](/Wikipedia:Biographies_of_living_persons)

Let us be unequivocally clear: [Wikipedia is not a manual, guidebook, textbook, or scientific journal](/Wikipedia:What_Wikipedia_is_not). Therefore, articles and all other encyclopedic content must be composed in a formal [tone](/Tone_(literature)). The specific standards for this formal tone may exhibit minor variations depending on the subject matter, but the general expectation is that it should mirror the style found in exemplary [Featured](/Wikipedia:Featured_articles)- and [Good](/Wikipedia:Good_articles)-class articles within the same category. Encyclopedic writing, by its very nature, adopts a fairly academic approach, yet it must simultaneously remain clear and readily understandable to a broad audience. A formal tone explicitly means that the article should eschew the use of [argot](/Argot), [slang](/Slang), [colloquialisms](/Colloquialism), [doublespeak](/Doublespeak), [legalese](/Legalese), or specialized [jargon](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style) that would be opaque to the average reader. It dictates that the English language be employed in a businesslike, precise manner (e.g., opting for "feel" or "atmosphere" instead of the lamentably vague "vibes"). This is not a forum for casual banter; it is a repository of knowledge.

#### Use of Pronouns

*   [Shortcuts](/Wikipedia:Shortcut)
*   • WP:PRONOUN[WP:PRONOUN](/Wikipedia:PRONOUN)
*   • WP:PRONOUNS[WP:PRONOUNS](/Wikipedia:PRONOUNS)
*   • WP:NARRATOR[WP:NARRATOR](/Wikipedia:NARRATOR)
*   "WP:PRONOUNS" redirects here. For information on the usage of pronouns in relation to gender identity, see [Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Biography § Gender identity](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Biography).
*   See also: [Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style § Pronouns](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style)

Articles are not personal narratives, nor are they instructional guides. Consequently, they must not be written from a [first-person](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style) ( *I/me/my* and *we/us/our* ) or [second-person](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style) ( *you* and *your* ) point of view. The first person inherently introduces a subjective perspective, which is fundamentally inconsistent with the [neutrality policy](/Wikipedia:Neutral_point_of_view). The second person, conversely, is inextricably linked with the step-by-step instructions of a how-to guide, which, as has been stated ad nauseam, [Wikipedia is not](/Wikipedia:What_Wikipedia_is_not). First- and second-person pronouns should, as a general rule, appear solely within attributed direct quotations that are directly relevant to the article's subject.

Naturally, there are always exceptions, because the universe abhors absolute rules. For instance, the "inclusive we" commonly employed in professional mathematics writing sometimes surfaces in articles to present and elucidate examples, though even for that subject, it is generally [discouraged on Wikipedia](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Mathematics).

A further consideration: strive to avoid gendered language whenever feasible. For example, prefer "the children" or "the actors" over the more restrictive "the boys and girls" or "the actors and actresses." The singular "they" serves as a perfectly acceptable alternative to the generic "he," or, more simply, sentences can be rephrased in the plural.
*   For a deeper dive into this area, consult [Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style § Identity](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style) and [Wikipedia:Gender-neutral_language](/Wikipedia:Gender-neutral_language).

#### News Style or Persuasive Writing

*   [Shortcuts](/Wikipedia:Shortcut)
*   • WP:NEWSSTYLE[WP:NEWSSTYLE](/Wikipedia:NEWSSTYLE)
*   • WP:PERSUASIVE[WP:PERSUASIVE](/Wikipedia:PERSUASIVE)

A Wikipedia article, under no circumstances, should [sound like a news article](/News_style). This is not a breaking story; it is a timeless repository of knowledge. Editors must assiduously avoid [bombastic wording](/Wikipedia:Neutral_point_of_view), clumsy attempts at humor or cleverness, an over-reliance on [primary sources](/Wikipedia:Identifying_reliable_sources), subjective [editorializing](/Wikipedia:No_original_research), the temporal bias of [recentism](/Wikipedia:Recentism), the visual distraction of [pull quotes](/Pull_quotes), the stylistic tics of [journalese](/Journalese), and the telegraphic shorthand of [headlinese](/Headlinese).

Similarly, and perhaps even more critically, [persuasive writing](/Persuasive_writing) has no place here. Such a style often exhibits many of the aforementioned faults, alongside its own unique array of transgressions, most frequently various forms of [appeals to emotion](/Appeals_to_emotion) and their associated [fallacies](/List_of_fallacies). This style is the domain of press releases, advertising copy, [editorial writing](/Editorial_writing), activism, propaganda, proposals, formal debate, reviews, and a significant portion of tabloid (and occasionally investigative) journalism. It is emphatically *not* Wikipedia's role to endeavor to convince the reader of anything. Its sole purpose is to furnish the salient facts, as accurately as they can be ascertained, and to provide the [reliable sources](/Wikipedia:Verifiability) that underpin them. The truth, such as it is, should speak for itself.

